<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,843,1991]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1037,1063]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A blind, colourless species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verhoeff" authorityYear="1919" box="[703,877,1037,1062]" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Alloschizidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[703,877,1037,1062]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Alloschizidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
characterized by short triangular dorsal scalesetae, a distinct groove along the frontal margin of the cephalon and along the lateral margin of pereonite 1, schisma of pereonite 1 with inner lobe distinctly shorter than outer one, wider than long trapezoidal telson, uropodal exopod as long as wide, and subquadrangular male pleopod 1 exopod.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,843,1991]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1191,1217]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Description.</emphasis>
Maximum length: 
<specimenCount box="[583,603,1193,1216]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity box="[621,716,1192,1218]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="14" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
; 
<specimenCount box="[730,750,1193,1216]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, 5.0 mm. Body colourless, strongly convex with vertical epimera, able to roll up into a perfect ball (
<figureCitation box="[660,769,1230,1256]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
). Back smooth, covered with numerous triangular scalesetae (
<figureCitation box="[225,330,1269,1295]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
); one line of noduli laterales per side on the pereonites, more or less at the same distance from the lateral margin (
<figureCitation box="[385,499,1308,1334]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
). Cephalon (
<figureCitation box="[656,801,1308,1334]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11C–D</figureCitation>
) with triangular scutellum slightly depressed in the middle; a distinct groove is present along the whole anterior margin of vertex; postscutellar line not visible, due to the presence of the cephalic groove; eyes absent. Pereonite 1 (
<figureCitation box="[966,1068,1385,1411]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
) with posterior margin slightly concave; postero-lateral schisma with outer lobe rounded and distinctly protruding backwards compared to inner one; lateral margin deeply grooved along its entire length, continuing the cephalic groove. Pereonite 2 (
<figureCitation box="[159,262,1501,1527]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11F</figureCitation>
) with a small triangular tooth on ventral side. Telson (
<figureCitation box="[910,1017,1501,1527]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11G</figureCitation>
) trapezoidal, wider than long, with slightly concave sides, wide, slightly convex apex. Antennula (
<figureCitation box="[886,990,1540,1566]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11H</figureCitation>
) of three articles, second article much shorter than the others; a tuft of about eight aesthetascs and a lobate appendix at the apex. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[1333,1427,1578,1604]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,256,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[187,1405,201,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-63@15.[182,1405,197,1897]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. (♀, paratype). A. Animal in lateral view, scale bar: 0.5 mm. B. Dorsal scale-seta. C. Cephalon, frontal. D. Cephalon, dorsal. E. Pereonite 1, dorsal. F. Pereonite 2, ventral. G. Pleonite 5, telson and uropods. H. Antennula. I. Antenna." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 11I</figureCitation>
) with flagellum as long as fifth article of peduncle; second flagellar article more than four times as long as first and bearing two rows of aesthetascs. Buccal pieces and respiratory structures on the pleopods as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Taiti &amp; Argano" authorityYear="2009" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Alloschizidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maymon">
<emphasis box="[1410,1428,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,250,1695,1720]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">maymon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Uropod (
<figureCitation box="[372,479,1694,1720]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="16.[151,257,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[181,1409,194,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-53@16.[176,1411,194,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 12. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. A. Uropod (♀, paratype). B–H. Male (paratype). B. Pereopod 1. C. Pereopod 7. D. Pleopod 1. E. Pleopod 2. F. Pleopod 3 exopod. G. Pleopod 4 exopod. H. Pleopod 5 exopod." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 12A</figureCitation>
) with exopod flattened, quadrangular, as long as wide; endopod distinctly longer than exopod.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,843,1991]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">
Male: Pereopod 1 (
<figureCitation box="[429,536,1772,1798]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="16.[151,257,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[181,1409,194,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-53@16.[176,1411,194,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 12. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. A. Uropod (♀, paratype). B–H. Male (paratype). B. Pereopod 1. C. Pereopod 7. D. Pleopod 1. E. Pleopod 2. F. Pleopod 3 exopod. G. Pleopod 4 exopod. H. Pleopod 5 exopod." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 12B</figureCitation>
) with some strong setae on carpus. Pereopod 7 (
<figureCitation box="[1124,1231,1772,1798]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="16.[151,257,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[181,1409,194,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-53@16.[176,1411,194,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 12. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. A. Uropod (♀, paratype). B–H. Male (paratype). B. Pereopod 1. C. Pereopod 7. D. Pleopod 1. E. Pleopod 2. F. Pleopod 3 exopod. G. Pleopod 4 exopod. H. Pleopod 5 exopod." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 12C</figureCitation>
) with no distinct sexual modifications, ischium with straight sternal margin. Pleopod 1 (
<figureCitation box="[1006,1115,1810,1836]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="16.[151,257,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[181,1409,194,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-53@16.[176,1411,194,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 12. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. A. Uropod (♀, paratype). B–H. Male (paratype). B. Pereopod 1. C. Pereopod 7. D. Pleopod 1. E. Pleopod 2. F. Pleopod 3 exopod. G. Pleopod 4 exopod. H. Pleopod 5 exopod." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 12D</figureCitation>
) exopod subquadrangular; endopod with a triangular apical part equipped with a row of short setae. Pleopod 2 (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1313,1849,1875]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="16.[151,257,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[181,1409,194,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-53@16.[176,1411,194,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 12. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. A. Uropod (♀, paratype). B–H. Male (paratype). B. Pereopod 1. C. Pereopod 7. D. Pleopod 1. E. Pleopod 2. F. Pleopod 3 exopod. G. Pleopod 4 exopod. H. Pleopod 5 exopod." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 12E</figureCitation>
) endopod thickset, distinctly longer than exopod. Pleopod 3-5 exopods as in 
<figureCitation box="[930,1069,1888,1914]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="16.[151,257,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[181,1409,194,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-53@16.[176,1411,194,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 12. Alloschizidium magrinii sp. nov. A. Uropod (♀, paratype). B–H. Male (paratype). B. Pereopod 1. C. Pereopod 7. D. Pleopod 1. E. Pleopod 2. F. Pleopod 3 exopod. G. Pleopod 4 exopod. H. Pleopod 5 exopod." pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Fig. 12F–H</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="52" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,843,1991]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,1926,1952]" pageId="14" pageNumber="52">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is named after our friend Dr. Paolo Magrini, a Florentine entomologist, who first collected this species near Montresta.
</paragraph>
